article.headline: Columbia 66, Harvard 57
article.story: NEW YORK (AP) -- Dalen Cuff scored eight of his 15 points in the second half and Columbia ended a 16-game home conference losing streak with a 66-57 win over Harvard on Friday night. Columbia, which also snapped a four-game losing streak overall, won an Ivy League game at home for the first time since Jan. 19, 2002. Harvard (3-19, 2-7) lost for the seventh time in eight games and got swept by Columbia in the season series for the first time since 1987. John-Michael Grzan's only points of the night came on a layup with 12:08 to play, starting an 11-2 run that enabled Columbia (7-15, 3-6) to pull away from a 39-39 tie to build a 50-41 lead. Columbia twice extended its lead to 14 points over the game's final five minutes before the Crimson scored the game's final five points. Dragutin Kravic and Matt Land each scored 11 points for Columbia, and Jeremiah Boswell added 10. Matt Stehle had a game-high 21 points and 12 rebounds for the Crimson but Kevin Rogus, Harvard's leading scorer, was held to just two points on a pair of second-half free throws.
